title: Euston Square Underground Station
description:
Gower Street entrance

Euston Square is a London Underground station at the corner of Euston Road and Gower Street, just north of University College London (not to be confused with nearby Euston tube station). The station, which is within walking distance of Euston railway station, is on the Circle, Hammersmith & City and Metropolitan lines, between Great Portland Street and King's Cross St. Pancras. It is in Zone 1 of the underground.

The station was built as "Gower Street", changing to its present name in 1909. In late 2006 the new entrance on the south side of Euston Road opened in a corner of the new headquarters of the Wellcome Trust replacing the old entrance.

In December 2005 Network Rail announced plans to create a subway link between the station and Euston station as part of the re-development of Euston station. This will create a direct link for users of heavy rail services which terminate at Euston.

Both Warren Street and Euston tube stations are within close walking distance.

title: St Martin-in-the-Fields
description:
St Martin-in-the-Fields is an Anglican church at Trafalgar Square, City of Westminster, London. Its patron is Saint Martin of Tours.
The earliest reference to the church is from 1222, with a dispute between the Abbot of Westminster and the Bishop of London as to who had control over it. The church was rebuilt by Henry VIII in 1542 to avoid plague victims from the area having to pass through his Palace of Whitehall. At this time, it was literally "in the fields" between the cities of Westminster and London.

http://www2.stmartin-in-the-fields.org/page/home/home.html

title: Her Majesty's Theatre
description:
Her Majesty's Theatre is the second oldest theatre still in use today in London, and dates back to 1705. The present building was constructed in 1897 by Herbert Beerbohm Tree who lived inside the building until his death in 1917. World War I smash Chu Chin Chow played for five years from 1916 which was a new record at the time. Since then, popular musicals have been staged at Her Majesty's including West Side Story, Fiddler on the Roof and The Phantom of the Opera, which opened in 1986 and is still going today.

title: Prince Edward Theatre
description:
The Prince Edward Theatre ( http://www.cheaptheatretickets.com/london/prince-edward-theatre/ ) opened in 1930 down the bustling side-streets of Soho but didn't see much success with its stage shows. In 1936 it was renamed as the London Casino, hosting caberet and variety shows and finally becoming a hit. In 1954 the Prince Edward was transformed into a cinema, hosting the popular films of the time including 2001: A Space Odyssey for a full year! In 1978 the theatre finally began hosting musicals and plays, with shows such as Evita, Mary Poppins, Jersey Boys and ABBA musical Mamma Mia! becoming successful.

title: Attorney General Office
description:
Her Majesty's Attorney General for England and Wales, usually known simply as the Attorney General, is the chief legal adviser of the Crown in England and Wales. The Attorney General represents the Queen and the Government in court, and has supervisory powers over prosecutions, which are the responsibility of the Director of Public Prosecutions and the Crown Prosecution Service. The Attorney General also represents the Crown in many judicial proceedings relating to the public interest, e.g. the administration of charities and income tax. The Attorney General is assisted by the Solicitor General for England and Wales: both offices are filled by political appointees who must belong to either house of Parliament. The Attorney General is not usually a member of the Cabinet, but is called to advise it when necessary.
20 Victoria Street, London SW1H 0NF
Tel: 020 7271 2492
Official website: http://www.attorneygeneral.gov.uk/
